# Java Spring Core

- Use constructor injection only. Do not add field injection or setter injection.
- Mark HTTP API classes with `@RestController`. Keep request mapping and transport concerns in controllers only.
- Put business rules in `@Service` classes. Do not move business logic into controllers or DTOs.
- Put database access in `@Repository` classes or Spring Data repositories. Do not query the database from controllers.
- Keep controllers thin: validate input, call one or more services, return the response.
- Keep service methods focused and explicit. Extract shared logic instead of duplicating branches across controllers.
- Write new code in Java 17 style. Prefer records, switch expressions, and clear immutable local variables when they fit the existing code.
- Follow the existing package split: `controller`, `service`, `repository`, `dto`, `model`, `security`.
- Reuse existing project flows before adding a new entry point or parallel architecture.
